\b \cf0 Norms\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\pardirnatural

\b0 \cf0 First, what is a normative fact? A normative fact \'93is what corresponds to a true normative statement\'94 (Schaber). For reasons of space, I shall ask you to join me in simply assuming normative realism. So, value-statements, reason-statements, and ought-statements are refer to different norms. (I will use \'93norm\'94 and \'93normative fact\'94 interchangeably). \'93You ought not hit strangers with a skateboard\'94 is a moral statement, but obviously, not every ought is a moral ought (Thomson 2001). \'93You ought to drink some hot lemonade\'94 is a prudential norm (Thomson 2001). Drinking the hot lemonade is something you aspire to, rather than a description of how you are behaving. If you do not, your throat may remain sore. Importantly, not every norm uses 
\i the word \'91ought\'92
\i0 . For example, \'93Eyes are for seeing,\'94 is a description of their function, purpose, or the end-directed activity of that system. \'93Eyes are for seeing\'94 is a normative 
\i and 
\i0 descriptive statement \'97 that\'92s what eyes do 
\i and 
\i0 what they ought to do. Eyes that cannot see are defective qua eye. \'93Wolves hunt in packs\'94 is a normative and descriptive statement. \
