\b \cf0 \
The basic thesis\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\pardirnatural

\b0 \cf0 So, the basic structure of the argument is this: there are two phenomena, two natural facts, that are best explained by the reality of natural normativity. If those two natural facts are real, then norms are part of nature, nature is normative. \
Consider those two natural facts: the first is end-directed (teleonomic) behavior of natural entities (eyes see, trees grow, stomachs digest); the second is the essentially normative (teleological) cognitive and practical activity of natural humans. The best explanation of each of these facts, and of both together, is that nature is normative.  By nature is normative, we could also say that there are natural teleological laws, natural norms, final causes, natural ends, natural functions. \
\
\pard\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\pardirnatural

\b \cf0 Aristotelian Categoricals 
\b0 \
\'93Wolves ought to hunt in packs\'94 is a statement Foot calls an Aristotelian Categorical (Foot 2002). An Aristotelian categorical is a statement of logical form neither universal nor particular. That is, to assert that all A\'92s \uc0\u966  is not to distribute \u966 -ing to all members of the category A, nor simply to assert that 
\i some 
\i0 A\'92s that we have observed were observed \uc0\u966 -ing. \
For example, \'93all reptiles lay eggs\'94 as universal categorical statement admits no exceptions.  The discovery of a new reptile, say, that gives live birth would not be the discovery of a 
\i defective
\i0  reptile, but a discovery of a new species of reptile. Or rather, it would mean that 
\i either
\i0  this newly discovered creature is not a reptile 
\i or 
\i0 that not all reptiles lay eggs. On the other hand, modestly confining oneself to a particular categorical statement like \'93some reptiles lay eggs\'94 would be radically unambitious science. Our sample size of reptiles that lay eggs is enormous; we are justified in making the inductive leap that 
\i all reptiles lay eggs. 
\i0 \
Aristotelian Categoricals, then, are neither simply universal nor simply particular categorical descriptions. They are normative/descriptive judgments. And they are also formed by observation and induction. For example, we observe that many As do indeed \uc0\u966 , and we infer that A 
\i is supposed to 
\i0 \uc0\u966 , A 
\i is for 
\i0 \uc0\u966 -ing.  Categorical are inductive generalizations with a normative character.  We have observed a sample of A\'92s \u966 -ing and we 
\i inductively infer 
\i0 that (perhaps) 
\i all 
\i0 A\'92s \uc0\u966 . On the basis of the generalization, the observation that a particular A does not \u966  does not refute a simply, universal predication but identifies a defect in that particular A. When we observe an exception to a categorical we do not ipso fact debunk our categorical nor are obliged to re-interpret our observation. When learn that all wolves (say) hunt in packs, and observe a wolf hunting alone, we do not debunk the principle that wolves hunt in packs. (Nor do we think that we have discovered a new species of canine that is morphologically and genetically identical to a wolf!) Rather, we have observed that not all wolves are doing what they are supposed to do, not all wolves perfectly exemplify their lifeform.\
